vey in the southern Miura Peninsula, Central Japan|last=Haeing Yoong|first=K.|year=2010|work=Geological Society of America Abstracts with Programs 42|page=106|accessdate=31 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210025633/https://gsa.confex.com/gsa/2010AM/finalprogram/abstract_180689.htm|archive-date=10 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the death toll has been reported as 23,024.<ref name=\"NGDC\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1361|08|03}}(G)<br>{{dts|1361|07|26}}(J) || 8.4 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||  || Sh\u014dhei earthquake || \u6b63\u5e73\u5357\u6d77\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dhei Nankai Jishin'' || {{coord|33.0|135.0|type:event}} || Triggered a tsunami.<ref>http://wwwsoc.nii.ac.jp/ssj/publications/HIGAI/before1600.html{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>http://www.histeq.jp/kaishi_23/23_021.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1498|09|20}}(G)<br>{{dts|1498|09|11}}(J) || 8.6 ''M<sub>K</sub>''||{{Hs|031000}}31,000<ref name=\"ngdc.noaa.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=7383&t=101650&s=13&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Significant Earthquake|author=Paula Dunbar|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1498 Nankai earthquake]] || \u660e\u5fdc\u5730\u9707 || ''Mei\u014d jishin'' || {{coord|34.0|138.1}} || Occurred off the coast of [[Nankaid\u014d|Nankai]], Japan, at about 08:00 local time on 20 September 1498. It had a [[Surface wave magnitude|magnitude]] estimated at 8.6<ref name=\"ngdc.noaa.gov\"/> MS and triggered a large tsunami. The death toll associated with this event is uncertain, but 31,000 casualties were reported.<ref>reported.http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=7383&t=101650&s=18&d=99,91,95,93&nd=display</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1586|01|18}} || 7.9 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||  || Tensho or Ise Bay earthquake || \u5929\u6b63\u5927\u5730\u9707 || ''Tensh\u014d Daijishin''|| || Some islands in Ise Bay reportedly disappeared<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7F5aZna9n6kC&pg=PA125|author1=Yuji Kanaori |author2=Kazuhiro Tanaka |author3=Masahiro Chigira | title= Engineering geological advances in Japan for the new millennium| publisher=Elsevier| year=2000|isbn=9780080530925 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gsj.jp/en/publications/reports/h10seika/10seika.html |author1=Toshihiko Sugai |author2=Yuichiro Fusejima |author3=Yasuo Awata |author4=Takashi Azuma |author5=Yoshihiko Kariya |author6=Yasuhiro Suzuki |title=Late Holocene paleoseismicity of the Yoro fault system |publisher=National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1605|02|03}} || 7.9 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|005000}}5,000+<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anshin.pref.tokushima.jp/normal/disaster_center/news.html?cid%3Ddisaster_center_126104359478%26nid%3D126665471905 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120308220426/http://anshin.pref.tokushima.jp/normal/disaster_center/news.html?cid=disaster_center_126104359478&nid=126665471905 |archivedate=2012-03-08 }}</ref>||[[1605 Nankai earthquake]] || \u6176\u9577\u5927\u5730\u9707 || ''Keich\u014d Daijishin'' ||{{coord|33.5|138.5}} || The 1605 Keich\u014d Nankaid\u014d earthquake occurred at about 20:00 local time on 3 February. It had an estimated magnitude of 7.9 on the [[surface wave magnitude]] scale and triggered a devastating tsunami that resulted in thousands of deaths in the Nankai and [[T\u014dkai region|T\u014dkai]] regions of [[Japan]]. It is uncertain whether there were two separate earthquakes separated by a short time interval or a single event. It is referred to as a [[tsunami earthquake]], in that the size of the tsunami greatly exceeds that expected from the magnitude of the earthquake.<ref name=\"Ishibashi\">{{cite journal|last=Ishibashi|first=K.|year=2004|title=Status of historical seismology in Japan|journal=Annals of Geophysics|volume=47|issue=2/3|pages=339\u2013368|url=http://www.earth-prints.org/bitstream/2122/763/1/02Ishibashi.pdf|accessdate=2009-11-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1611|09|27}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|003700}}3,700+ (Official estimate) || 1611 Aizu earthquake || \u4f1a\u6d25\u5730\u9707 || ''Aizu Jishin'' || Aizu basin, (Present day of [[Fukushima Prefecture]]) || According to official estimated report, more than 3,700 human fatalities. [[Aizuwakamatsu Castle]], many temples, and 20,000 houses collapsed in the damaged areas.\n|-\n| {{dts|1611|12|02}} || 8.1 ||{{Hs|002000}}2,000+ ||[[1611 Sanriku earthquake]] || \u6176\u9577\u4e09\u9678\u5730\u9707 || ''Keicho Sanriku Daijishin'' || {{coord|39.0|144.4}} || Occurred on December 2, 1611 with an epicenter off the [[Sanriku]] coast in Iwate Prefecture. The [[Moment magnitude scale|magnitude]] of the [[earthquake]] was 8.1M.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hnn.us/articles/139314.html|title=History News Network - Danger in the Lowground: The Japan Earthquake in Historical Context|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1662|6|16}} || 7.25 \u2013 7.6 M || 700\u2013900<ref>[http://www.bousai.go.jp/kyoiku/kyokun/kyoukunnokeishou/rep/1662_kanbun_omiwakasa_jishin/index.html \u5831\u544a\u66f8\uff081662 \u5bdb\u6587\u8fd1\u6c5f\u30fb\u82e5\u72ed\u5730\u9707\uff09] Cebinet Office\uff08Japan\uff09Retrieved 2018-03-05</ref>|| 1662 Kanbun \u014cmi and Wakasa earthquake || \u5bdb\u6587\u8fd1\u6c5f\u30fb\u82e5\u72ed\u5730\u9707 || ''kanbun \u014cmi wakasa jishin'' || [[Lake Biwa]] south || Strong tremor in \u014cmi \u00b7 Wakasa area. This earthquake is causing crustal deformation (East of [[Lake Suigetsu]]: Rose 4.5 meter).<ref>Susumu Yamaga\u300c\u65e5\u672c\u5217\u5cf6\u306e\u5730\u9707\u30fb\u6d25\u6ce2\u30fb\u5674\u706b\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u300dpp.&nbsp;72-73.2018-03-05 Reading. {{ISBN|978-4-86064-476-5}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1667|}} || 8.5 \u2013 9.0 M || unknown || 1667 Kanbun Tokachi-oki earthquake || \u5bdb\u6587\u30fb\u5341\u52dd\u6c96\u5730\u9707 (scientific) || ''kanbun Tokachi-oki jishin'' || Offshore Tokachi region || Inferred earthquake from tsunami deposits near Kushiro, Kuril Trench rupture.  No record as the region was not yet under Japanese control. <ref>https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/pdf/10.1098/rsta.2014.0375 Geological and historical evidence of irregular recurrent earthquakes in Japan</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201902150001.html |title = Scientists warn Hokkaido about 'imminent' megaquake\uff1aThe Asahi Shimbun}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1677|11|04}} || 8.3\u20138.6 ''{{M|w}}'' || {{Hs|000569}} 569 || [[1677 B\u014ds\u014d earthquake]] ||  || || Offshore [[B\u014ds\u014d Peninsula]] || This earthquake was felt with low intensity, but generated a large tsunami that killed 569 people. It is thought to have ruptured the interface between the Pacific Plate and the Okhotsk Plate at the southern end of the Japan Trench.<ref name=\"Yanagisawa_etal_2016\">{{Cite journal |last=Yanagisawa |first=H. |last2=Goto |first2=K. |last3=Sugawara |first3=D. |last4=Kanamaru |first4=K. |last5=Iwamoto |first5=N. |last6=Takamori |first6=Y. |year=2016 |title=Tsunami earthquake can occur elsewhere along the Japan Trench\u2014Historical and geological evidence for the 1677 earthquake and tsunami |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth |volume=121 |issue=5 |doi=10.1002/2015JB012617}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1703|12|31}} || 8.0 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|005233}} 5,233 ||[[1703 Genroku earthquake]] || \u5143\u7984\u5927\u5730\u9707 || ''Genroku Daijishin'' || [[Edo]] || This earthquake shook Edo and killed an estimated 2,300 people. The earthquake is thought to have been an interplate earthquake whose focal region extended from [[Sagami Bay]] to the tip of the [[B\u014ds\u014d Peninsula]] as well as the area along the [[Sagami Trough]] in the open sea southeast of the Boso Peninsula. This earthquake then resulted in a [[tsunami]] which hit the coastal areas of the Boso Peninsula and Sagami Bay. The tsunami was reported to have caused more than 10,000 fatalities.\n|-\n| {{dts|1707|10|28}} || 8.6 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|005000}}5,000+ ||[[1707 H\u014dei earthquake]] || \u5b9d\u6c38\u5730\u9707 || ''H\u014dei jishin'' || Off the [[Kii Peninsula]] || Struck both the [[Nankaid\u014d]] and [[T\u014dkai region]]s, causing moderate to severe damage throughout southwestern [[Honshu]], [[Shikoku]] and southeastern [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref name=\"Miyazawa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dpri.kyoto-u.ac.jp/dat/nenpo/no48/48c0/a48c0p13.pdf |title=Historical maximum seismic intensity maps in Japan from 1586 to 2004: construction of database and application |last=Miyazawa |first=M. |author2=Mori J. |year=2005 |work=Ann. Disaster Prev. Res. Inst. Kyoto Univ. |volume=48C |accessdate=30 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722072314/https://www.dpri.kyoto-u.ac.jp/dat/nenpo/no48/48c0/a48c0p13.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1771|04|24}} || 7.4 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|013486}}13,486<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=1405&t=101650&s=13&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Significant Earthquake| author=Paula Dunbar|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1771 Great Yaeyama Tsunami]] || \u516b\u91cd\u5c71\u5730\u9707 || ''Yaeyama jishin'' || {{coord|24.0|124.3}} || The 1771 Great Yaeyama Tsunami (also called \u660e\u548c\u306e\u5927\u6d25\u6ce2, the Great Tsunami of Meiwa) was caused by the Yaeyama Great Earthquake at about 8 A.M. on April 24. 13,486 people (including 9,313 in [[Yaeyama Islands]] (8,815 in [[Ishigaki Island]]), 2,548 in [[Miyako Islands]] and 1,625 in other areas) were confirmed to be dead or missing and more than 3,000 houses were destroyed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The height of the [[tsunami]] was over 40 meters at [[Ishigaki Island]], up to a maximum of 85.4 meters in the village called Miyara. In [[Tarama]], estimated tsunami runup height was approximately 18 meters. To this day, boulders reportedly launched by the tsunami (called \"tsunami stones\") remain in the northwestern highlands of [[Miyakojima]]. According to unverified local legend, a small unnamed [[island]] in the area was swallowed by the tsunami and disappeared.\n|-\n| {{dts|1792|05|21}} || 6.4 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|015448}}15,448<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=1515&t=101650&s=13&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Significant Earthquake|author=Paula Dunbar|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1792 Unzen earthquake and tsunami]] || \u5cf6\u539f\u5927\u5909\u80a5\u5f8c\u8ff7\u60d1 || ''Unzen jishin''<br>(''Shimabara Taihen Higo Meiwaku'') || {{coord|32.8|130.3}} ||[[File:Ariake sea coastline.png|thumb|Changes to the Ariake Sea coastline, in the center of Mount Unzen, Kumamoto Prefecture (right) and the Amakusa Islands (see below) were affected by the tsunami]] An earthquake caused by volcanic activity of [[Mount Unzen]] (in the Shimabara Peninsula [[Nagasaki]], Japan). It killed 15,000 people altogether, due in large part to a tsunami that was triggered by the collapse of nearby Mount Mayuyama's southern flank into the bay. The incident is also referred to with the phrase '[[Shimabara, Nagasaki|Shimabara]] erupted, Higo affected' (\u5c9b\u539f\u5927\u5909\u80a5\u540e\u8ff7\u60d1), as many people in Higo, ([[Kumamoto]], located 20&nbsp;km away across the [[Ariake Sea]]) were also killed by the resulting tsunami, which then bounced back to hit Shimabara again.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1828|12|18}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|001559}}1,559 (official confirmed) || 1828 Echigo Sanj\u014d earthquake || \u8d8a\u5f8c\u4e09\u6761\u5730\u9707 || ''Echigo Sanj\u014d Jishin'' || [[Sanjo, Niigata|Sanjo, Niigata Prefecture]] (then [[Echigo Province]]) || According to the official confirmed report, 21,134 houses and buildings were damaged, and 1,204 of them burned down. There were 1,559 human fatalities, and 2,666 injured people in the affected area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1847|05|08}} || 7.3 M ||{{Hs|008600}}8,600+ ||[[1847 Nagano earthquake]] || \u5584\u5149\u5bfa\u5730\u9707 || ''Zenk\u014dji Jishin'' || Nagano Basin (then [[Shinano Province]])|| In the central area of Nagano, many buildings collapsed, including Zenk\u014dji temple. The earthquake triggered a complex variety of resulting disasters, which included fires, landslides, and flooding due to the formation and subsequent collapse of a \"dam\" made of debris from the collapsed buildings. According to the confirmed official report, the death toll throughout the region reached at least 8,600. 21,000 houses were damaged and 3,400 burned, and an additional 44,000 homes were damaged by the landslides in the area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1854|07|09}} || 7.25 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000995}}995 (official confirmed) || 1854 Iga Ueno earthquake || \u4f0a\u8cc0\u4e0a\u91ce\u5730\u9707 || ''Iga Ueno Jishin'' || [[Iga, Mie|Iga, Mie Prefecture]] (then [[Iga Province]]) || According to the official confirmed report, 2,576 houses and buildings were damaged, with 995 human fatalities and 994 injures in the affected area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1854|12|23}} || 8.4 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|002000}}2,000 (estimated)<ref name=\"Usami\">{{cite journal|last=Usami|first=T.|year=1979|title=Study of Historical Earthquakes in Japan|journal=Bulletin of the Earthquake Research Institute|volume=54|pages=399\u2013439|url=http://repository.dl.itc.u-tokyo.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/2261/12734/1/ji0543001.pdf|accessdate=2009-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722080425/http://repository.dl.itc.u-tokyo.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/2261/12734/1/ji0543001.pdf|archive-date=2011-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>||[[1854 T\u014dkai earthquake]] || \u5b89\u653f\u6771\u6d77\u5730\u9707 || ''Ansei T\u014dkai Jishin'' || [[Suruga Bay]] || The [[epicenter]] ranged from Suruga Bay to the deep ocean, and the quake struck primarily in the [[T\u014dkai region]], but destroyed houses as far away as in [[Edo]]. The accompanying [[tsunami]] caused damage along the entire coast from the [[B\u014ds\u014d Peninsula]] in modern-day [[Chiba prefecture]] to [[Tosa province]] (modern-day [[K\u014dchi Prefecture]]).<ref name=Kawade>Kawade Shob\u014d Shinsha Editorial Team (eds.). \"Ansei Daijishin\" (\u5b89\u653f\u5927\u5730\u9707, \"Great Earthquakes of Ansei\"). ''\u014c-Edo Rekishi Hyakka'' (\u5927\u6c5f\u6238\u6b74\u53f2\u767e\u79d1, \"Historical Encyclopedia of Great Edo\"). Tokyo: Kawade Shob\u014d Shinsha Publishers, 2007, p. 253.</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1854|12|24}} || 8.4 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|010000}}10,000+ ||[[1854 Nankai earthquake]] || \u5b89\u653f\u5357\u6d77\u5730\u9707 || ''Ansei Nankai Jishin'' || [[Nankai Trough]] || Over 10,000 people from the T\u014dkai region down to Kyushu were killed.<ref name=Kawade/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1855|11|11}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|006641 !}}6,641 ||[[1855 Edo earthquake]] || \u5b89\u653f\u6c5f\u6238\u5730\u9707 || ''Ansei Edo Jishin'' || [[Edo]], near the mouth of the [[Arakawa River (Kanto)|Arakawa River]] || One hundred and twenty earthquakes and tremors in total were felt in Edo in 1854\u201355. The great earthquake struck after 10 o'clock in the evening; roughly 30 aftershocks ensued, continuing until dawn.  Records from the time indicate 6,641 deaths inside the city and 2,759 injuries; much of the city was destroyed by fire, leading many people to stay in rural inns. Aftershocks continued for twenty days.<ref name=Kawade/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1858|04|09}} || 7.0 ||{{Hs|000200}}200\u2013300 ||[[1858 Hietsu earthquake]] || \u98db\u8d8a\u5730\u9707|\u98db\u8d8a\u5730\u9707 || ''Hietsu Jishin'' || Atotsugawa Fault || It occurred on the Atotsugawa Fault, which connects [[Mount Tate]] in [[Toyama Prefecture]] and the Am\u014d Pass in [[Gifu Prefecture]] on the island of [[Honsh\u016b]] in [[Japan]].  Its name includes one [[kanji]] from {{Nihongo|[[Hida Province|Hida]]|\u98db\u9a28\u56fd}} and one from {{Nihongo|[[Etch\u016b Province|Etch\u016b]]|\u8d8a\u4e2d\u56fd}}, the names of the provinces that were in use at the time. The earthquake is estimated to have killed 200\u2013300 people.  It also caused the Mount Tonbi Landslide and blocked the upper reaches of the [[J\u014dganji River]].<ref name=\"Hietsu\">{{cite web|url=http://cais.gsi.go.jp/KAIHOU/kaihou33/03_05.pdf|title=The Hietsu Earthquake of April 9, 1858 and the Omachi Earthquake of April 23, 1858|last=Usami|first=Tatsuo|language=Japanese|publisher=Earthquake Research Institute, University of Tokyo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304141331/http://cais.gsi.go.jp/KAIHOU/kaihou33/03_05.pdf|archivedate=March 4, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1872|03|18}} || 7.1 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000551}}551 (official confirmed) || 1872 Hamada earthquake || \u6d5c\u7530\u5730\u9707 || ''Hamada Jishin'' || off coast [[Hamada, Shimane|Hamada, Shimane Prefecture]] || According to the official confirmed report, 4506 houses were damaged by the earthquake, 230 houses were burned, 551 people were killed, and landslides destroyed 6567 homes in the affected area. This quake occurred at 16:40 local time.\n|-\n| {{dts|1880|02|22}} || 5.5\u20136.0 || 0 || 1880 Yokohama earthquake || \u6a2a\u6d5c\u5730\u9707 || ''Yokohama Jishin'' || Yokohama City || The damage was minor. However, the [[Seismological Society of Japan]] was established in response to the quake.<ref>[https://typhoon.yahoo.co.jp/weather/calendar/173/ \u6a2a\u6d5c\u5730\u9707\uff081880\u5e74\uff09] Japan,Yahoo\uff08Japanese\uff09Retrieval 2018/04/06</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1889|07|28}} || 6.3 ||{{Hs|000020}}20 ||[[1889 Kumamoto earthquake]] || \u718a\u672c\u5730\u9707|\u718a\u672c\u5730\u9707 ||''Kumamoto Jishin'' || Tatsuda fault || First major earthquake after the establishment of the [[Seismological Society of Japan]] in 1880.\n|-\n| {{dts|1891|10|28}} || 8.0 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|007273}}7,273 ||[[1891 Mino\u2013Owari earthquake]] || \u7f8e\u6fc3\u30fb\u5c3e\u5f35\u5730\u9707 || ''Mino Owari Jishin'' || [[Neodani Fault]] || A large earthquake that struck the former [[Provinces of Japan|provinces]] of [[Mino Province|Mino]] and [[Owari Province|Owari]] in the [[N\u014dbi Plain]] area during the [[Meiji period]] in [[Japan]]. It is also referred to as the '''N\u014dbi Earthquake''' (\u6fc3\u5c3e\u5730\u9707 ''N\u014dbi Jishin'') or the '''Great N\u014dbi Earthquake''' (\u6fc3\u5c3e\u5927\u5730\u9707 ''N\u014dbi Daijishin'').\n|-\n| {{dts|1894|06|20}} || 6.6 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000031}}31 ||[[1894 Tokyo earthquake]] || \u660e\u6cbb\u6771\u4eac\u5730\u9707 || ''Meiji-Tokyo Jishin'' || [[Tokyo Bay]] || This earthquake occurred in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] at 14:04 on June 20, 1894. It affected downtown Tokyo and neighboring [[Kanagawa prefecture]], especially the cities of [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]] and [[Yokohama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencelinks.jp/j-east/article/199920/000019992099A0772172.php|title=Source Parameters of the Tokyo Earthquake in Meiji Era (1894).|publisher=Japan Science and Technology Agency|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730040328/http://sciencelinks.jp/j-east/article/199920/000019992099A0772172.php|archivedate=2009-07-30}}</ref> The depth of the 1894 earthquake has not been determined, but it is thought to have occurred within the subducting [[Pacific Plate]] under the [[Kant\u014d region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hp1039.jishin.go.jp/eqchreng/5-1-3.htm|title=Inland earthquakes|publisher=The Headquarters for Earthquake Research Promotion}}</ref> The death toll was 31 killed and 157 injured.\n|-\n| {{dts|1894|10|22}} || 7.0 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000726}}726 (Official confirmed) || 1894 Sh\u014dkai earthquake || \u5e84\u5185\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dnai Jishin'' || [[Sakata, Yamagata|Sakata]], [[Yamagata Prefecture]] || According to the official confirmed report, 14,118 houses and buildings were damaged and 2,148 were burned. There were 726 human fatalities and 8,403 people injured in the damaged area. A large-scale fire broke out in Sakata, and around the Shonai plain area, many instances of cracked earth, sinking ground, sand boils, and fountains were observed.\n|-\n| {{dts|1896|06|15}} || 8.5 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|022000}}22,000+<ref>{{cite web| url= https://earthquake.usgs.gov/learn/today/index.php?month=6&day=15&submit=View+Date| title=Today in Earthquake History|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1896 Sanriku earthquake]] || \u660e\u6cbb\u4e09\u9678\u5730\u9707 || ''Meiji Sanriku Jishin'' || &nbsp; || This quake occurred off the coast of [[Sanriku, Iwate|Sanriku]] in [[Iwate Prefecture]], which caused a [[tsunami]] of {{convert|25|m|ft|abbr=on}} to strike 35 minutes after the quake, destroying hundreds of houses and killed over 22,000 people. Tsunami were also observed as far away as Hawaii and in California.<ref name=\"meijisanriku-agu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agu.org/news/press/pr_archives/1996-1999/sanriku.html|title=Research describes origin of devastating tsunami|publisher=American Geophysical Union|date=1996-06-12|accessdate=2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name=\"meijisanriku-usgs\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1896_06_15.php|title=Historic Earthquakes: Sanriku, Japan, 1896 June 15 UTC , Magnitude 8.5|publisher=[[US Geological Survey]]|date=2009-01-29|accessdate=2009-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509154555/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1896_06_15.php|archive-date=2009-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1923|09|01}} || 8.3 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|142800}} 142,800<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/learn/today/index.php?month=9&day=1&submit=View+Date|title=Today in Earthquake History|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1923 Great Kant\u014d earthquake]] || \u5927\u6b63\u95a2\u6771\u5730\u9707<br>(\u95a2\u6771\u5927\u9707\u707d) || ''Taish\u014d Kant\u014d Jishin''<br>(''Kant\u014d Daishinsai'') || [[Izu \u014cshima]] || An earthquake which struck the [[Kant\u014d]] plain on the [[Japan]]ese main island of [[Honsh\u016b]] at 11:58 on the morning of September 1, 1923.  Varied accounts hold that the duration of the earthquake was between 4 and 10 minutes. The quake had an epicenter deep beneath [[Izu \u014cshima]] Island in [[Sagami Bay]]. It devastated [[Tokyo]], the port city of [[Yokohama]], and the surrounding prefectures of [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], and [[Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka]], and caused widespread damage throughout the Kant\u014d region.<ref>Hammer, Joshua. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=6O8VyhDbUPgC  ''Yokohama Burning: the Deadly 1923 Earthquake and Fire that Helped Forge the Path to World War II,'' p. 278], citing Francis Hawks,  (1856). ''Narrative of the Expedition of an American Squadron to the China Seas and Japan Performed in the Years 1852, 1853 and 1854 under the Command of Commodore M.C. Perry, United States Navy,'' Washington: A.O.P. Nicholson by order of Congress, 1856; originally published in ''Senate Executive Documents'', No. 34 of 33rd Congress, 2nd Session.</ref>  The power and intensity of the earthquake is easy to underestimate, but the 1923 earthquake managed to move the 93-ton [[K\u014dtoku-in|Great Buddha]] statue at [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]].  The statue slid forward almost two feet.<ref>Great Buddha: [http://pacific-islander.blogspot.com/2007/10/all-buddhas-great-and-small.html blog]</ref> Casualty estimates range up to about 142,800 deaths, a figure including approximately 40,000 who went missing and were presumed dead.\n|-\n| {{dts|1925|05|23}} || 6.8 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000428}}428 ||1925 Kita Tajima earthquake || \u5317\u4f46\u99ac\u5730\u9707 || ''Kita Tajima Jishin'' || [[Toyooka]] in [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]] ||This earthquake's epicenter was (35.6 degrees north latitude, 134.8 degrees east longitude), in the Maruyama River estuary. According to the Japanese government's official report, there were 428 human fatalities, 1,016 people injured, 7,863 buildings destroyed, and 45,659 houses damaged by collapse or fire. This quake caused extensive damage to the town of Toyooka and the Maruyama River area. Just before the shaking could be felt, a sound like a cannon was reportedly heard intermittently from the direction of the estuary near the Maruyama River. During the earthquake, the ground in the town of Tokyooka experienced strong seismic vibrations for 16 seconds. As most of the buildings of the time were wooden, many of them were destroyed at once during the initial earthquake. In the fire that broke out subsequently, half of Toyooka was burned down, with many deaths resulting (a reported 8% of the town's population.) 272 deaths were confirmed to have occurred in the Kinosaki area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1927|03|07}} || 7.6 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|003020}}3,020 ||[[1927 Kita Tango earthquake]] || \u5317\u4e39\u5f8c\u5730\u9707 || ''Kita Tango Jishin'' || [[Tango Peninsula]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]] || Almost all of the houses in Mineyama (now part of [[Ky\u014dtango, Kyoto|Ky\u014dtango]]) were destroyed, and the quake was felt as far away as [[Tokyo]] and [[Kagoshima]].<ref name=\"kitatango-usgs\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1927_03_07.php|title=Historic Earthquakes: Tango, Japan, 1927 March 07 09:27 UTC, Magnitude 7.6|publisher=[[USGS]]|accessdate=2009-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509130409/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1927_03_07.php|archive-date=2009-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1930|11|26}} || 7.3 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000272}}272 ||[[1930 North Izu earthquake]] || 1930\u5e74\u5317\u4f0a\u8c46\u5730\u9707 || ''Sen-ky\u016bhyaku-sanj\u016b-nen Kita-Izu Jishin'' || [[Izu Peninsula]] || \n|-\n| {{dts|1933|03|02}} || 8.4 ''M<sub>w</sub>''<ref>Kanamori, H. ( 1977), [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/4982/ce0d7cef9194cc5d95fc823bb888c3eae505.pdf The energy release in great earthquakes], J.