s</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000025}}25 ||[[1974 Izu Peninsula earthquake]] || 1974\u5e74\u4f0a\u8c46\u534a\u5cf6\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Sen-ky\u016bhyaku-nanaj\u016byo-nen Izu-hant\u014d-oki Jishin'' || near [[Izu Peninsula]] || \n|-\n| {{dts|1978|06|12}} || 7.7 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000028}}28 ||[[1978 Miyagi earthquake]] || \u5bae\u57ce\u770c\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Miyagi-ken-oki jishin'' || just offshore [[Miyagi Prefecture]] || Damage was greatest around [[Sendai]], and the earthquake triggered widespread landslides.<ref name=\"USGS1978\">{{cite web| url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eqarchives/significant/sig_1978.php| title=Significant Earthquakes of the World 1978|last=USGS|accessdate=6 July 2010| url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100123173040/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eqarchives/significant/sig_1978.php|archivedate=23 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Sidle\">{{cite book| last1=Sidle |first1=R.C. |last2=Pearce |first2=A.J. |last3=O'Loughlin |first3=C.L. |title=Hillslope stability and land use  |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eRq20MrJhBUC| volume=11| year =1985|publisher=American Geophysical Union|isbn=978-0-87590-315-6|pages=1\u20139|chapter=1 Significance of Soil Mass Movement}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1983|05|26}} || 7.8 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000104}}104 ||[[1983 Sea of Japan earthquake]] || \u65e5\u672c\u6d77\u4e2d\u90e8\u5730\u9707 || ''Nihonkai-chubu jishin'' || off coast 50 miles (80 kilometers)from [[Noshiro, Akita|Noshiro, Akita Prefecture]] ||Rising up to 30 feet (10 meters) above the coastline, the tsunami created by this earthquake was observed throughout a wide area along the Sea of Japan's coast and caused damage from [[Tsuruoka]] to [[Goshogawara]]. 100 people lost their lives to the tsunami, including seawall construction workers and beachgoers. In total, 104 people were killed. Soil liquification was widely observed through the affected area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1984|09|14}} || 6.3 ''M<sub>s</sub>''