{convert|55|km|mi|abbr=on}} due east of the [[Oshika Peninsula]] in [[Miyagi Prefecture]] || A powerful [[earthquake]] that struck the east coast of the [[Japan]]ese island of [[Honsh\u016b]] at 11:46 (02:46 [[UTC]]) on August 16, causing casualties, building collapses and [[power outage]]s.  The earthquake began on Tuesday, August 16, 2005, and affected Japan's northeastern coast. It triggered a tsunami warning, and buildings shook 200 miles away in the capital, Tokyo. It was initially estimated to have a rating of 6.8., and the U.S. Geological Survey later registered it as a 7.2.<ref>{{cite web|date=August 16, 2005 |title=Quake Shakes Buildings in Tokyo |work=The Associated Press |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/07/light-quake-shakes-buildings-in-tokyo-no-injuries-or-damage.html |accessdate=2006-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207185046/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/07/light-quake-shakes-buildings-in-tokyo-no-injuries-or-damage.html |archivedate=February 7, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|11|15}} || 8.3 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000000}}0 ||[[2006 Kuril Islands earthquake]] || 2006\u5e74\u5343\u5cf6\u5217\u5cf6\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Nisen-roku-nen Chishima Rett\u014d Oki Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Kuril Islands</span> about {{convert|160|km|mi|abbr=on}} due east of the southern tip of [[Simushir]] in the [[Kuril Islands]] || The earthquake happened at 20:29 [[Japan Standard Time|JST]] on November 15, 2006, causing a [[tsunami]] to hit the Japanese northern coast.\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|01|13}} || 8.1 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000000}}0 ||[[2007 Kuril Islands earthquake]] || 2007\u5e74\u5343\u5cf6\u5217\u5cf6\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Nisen-nana-nen Chishima Rett\u014d Oki Jishin'' ||  {{coord|46|28.8|N|154|04.48|E|type:event}} || The earthquake happened at 1:23&nbsp;p.m. [[Japan Standard Time|JST]]  (04:23 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) and resulted in a [[tsunami]] warning but did not cause significant damage.<ref name=GIANT-EARTHQUAKE-HITS-JAPAN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/jan2007/2007-01-12-06.asp|title=Giant Earthquake Jolts Japan, But Tsunami Warnings Cancelled|last=staff|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref> The epicentre was located 95&nbsp;km to the south east of the [[2006 Kuril Islands earthquake]] that struck a few weeks earlier.\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|03|25}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000001}}1 ||[[2007 Noto earthquake]] || \u80fd\u767b\u534a\u5cf6\u5730\u9707 || ''Noto Hant\u014d Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Ishikawa Prefecture</span>about {{convert|11|km|mi|abbr=on}} due west of the southern end of the town of [[Wajima, Ishikawa|Wajima]] || At 9:42&nbsp;a.m., a [[Richter magnitude scale|magnitude]] 6.9 [[earthquake]], struck the [[Hokuriku region]] of Japan, near the [[Noto Peninsula]]. The earthquake shook the city of [[Nanao, Ishikawa|Nanao]] and the town of [[Anamizu, Ishikawa|Anamizu]] with a [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|seismic intensity]] of 6+ on Japan's [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|''shindo'' scale]]. One death, in the city of [[Wajima, Ishikawa|Wajima]], and at least 214 injuries have been reported.  A [[tsunami]] advisory was immediately made for the [[Kaga, Ishikawa|Kaga]] coast and Noto coast, and a 10\u201320&nbsp;cm wave hit shore about 30 minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070326a1.html|title=Hokuriku quake kills one, injures 170|publisher=[[The Japan Times]]|date=2007-03-26}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|07|16}} || 6.6 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000011}}11 ||[[2007 Ch\u016betsu offshore earthquake]] || \u65b0\u6f5f\u770c\u4e2d\u8d8a\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Niigata-ken Ch\u016betsu Oki Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Niigata Prefecture</span>about {{convert|29|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]] || The earthquake<ref name=\"JMA\">{{cite web| url = http://www.jma.go.jp/jma/press/0707/16b/kaisetsu200707161450.pdf| title = 2007 \u5e74\uff17\u670816 \u65e510 \u664213 \u5206\u3053\u308d\u65b0\u6f5f\u770c\u4e0a\u4e2d\u8d8a\u6c96\u3067\u767a\u751f\u3057\u305f\u5730\u9707\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066| publisher = [[Japan Meteorological Agency]]| date = 2007-07-16| accessdate = 2007-07-19| language=Japanese}}</ref>) was a powerful [[Richter magnitude scale|magnitude]] 6.6 [[earthquake]]<ref name=\"jnr\">{{cite web|title=Powerful earthquake strikes Niigata, causes leak at nuclear power plant| url= http://www.japannewsreview.com/society/chubu/20070716page_id=754 |publisher=Japan News Review|date=2007-07-16| url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317143212/http://www.japannewsreview.com/society/chubu/20070716page_id=754|archivedate=2011-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/national/update/0716/TKY200707160041.html|title=asahi.com\uff1a\u65b0\u6f5f\u3001\u9577\u91ce\u3067\u9707\u5ea6\uff16\u5f37 \uff18\u4eba\u6b7b\u4ea1\u3001\uff19\uff10\uff18\u4eba\u304c\u3051\u304c - \u793e\u4f1a<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> that occurred 10:13&nbsp;a.m. [[Japan Standard Time|local time]] (01:13 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on July 16, 2007, in the northwest [[Niigata Prefecture|Niigata region]] of Japan. The earthquake shook Niigata and neighbouring prefectures. The city of [[Kashiwazaki, Niigata|Kashiwazaki]] and the villages of [[Iizuna, Nagano|Iizuna]] and [[Kariwa, Niigata|Kariwa]] registered the highest [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|seismic intensity]] of a strength 6 on Japan's [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|''shindo'' scale]], but the quake was felt as far away as Tokyo.<ref name=\"jnr\"/> Eleven deaths and at least 1,000 injuries have been reported, and 342 buildings were completely destroyed, mostly older wooden structures.<ref name=\"jnr\"/><ref>[http://www.japannewsreview.com/society/chubu/20070723page_id=964 Niigata earthquake death toll rises to eleven] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103072457/http://www.japannewsreview.com/society/chubu/20070723page_id=964 |date=2013-11-03 }} [http://www.japannewsreview.com Japan News Review], July 23</ref><ref name=\"CNN Niigata\">{{cite news|title=Japanese nuke plant leaked after earthquake |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/07/16/japan.quake.ap/index.html |publisher=AP via CNN |date=2007-07-16 |accessdate=2007-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810232526/http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/07/16/japan.quake.ap/index.html#cnnSTCVideo |archivedate=August 10, 2007 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2008|06|14}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000012}}12 ||[[2008 Iwate\u2013Miyagi Nairiku earthquake]] || \u5ca9\u624b\u30fb\u5bae\u57ce\u5185\u9678\u5730\u9707 || ''Iwate Miyagi Nairiku Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Iwate Prefecture</span>about {{convert|1|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of Narusawa Onsen in northwest [[Iwate Prefecture]] || This earthquake struck the central [[T\u014dhoku region]], in northeastern [[Honsh\u016b]], Japan.<ref name=\"JMA-tremors\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seisvol.kishou.go.jp/cgi-bin/shindo_db.cgi?from_YYYY=2008&from_MM=06&from_DD=14&from_hh=08&from_mm=00&to_YYYY=2008&to_MM=06&to_DD=14&to_hh=12&to_mm=00&ORG_PID=14516&pref=0&minimum_shindo=1&max_count=50&PARAM_OK_DATE=%B8%A1%BA%F7%BC%C2%B9%D4|title=Result of searching the database of felt earthquakes|publisher=[[Japan Meteorological Agency]]|language=Japanese}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2009|08|11}} || 6.6 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000001}}1 ||[[2009 Shizuoka earthquake]] || \u99ff\u6cb3\u6e7e\u5730\u9707 || ''Suruga-wan Jishin'' || {{coord|33.8|N|138.50|E}}, depth 20.0&nbsp;km ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/national/view/m66-quake-jolts-shizuoka-pref-and-vicinity-disrupting-trains|title=M6.5 quake jolts Shizuoka Pref, injuring more than 20|date=2009-08-09|publisher=Kyodo|accessdate=2009