000200}}200\u2013300 ||[[1858 Hietsu earthquake]] || \u98db\u8d8a\u5730\u9707|\u98db\u8d8a\u5730\u9707 || ''Hietsu Jishin'' || Atotsugawa Fault || It occurred on the Atotsugawa Fault, which connects [[Mount Tate]] in [[Toyama Prefecture]] and the Am\u014d Pass in [[Gifu Prefecture]] on the island of [[Honsh\u016b]] in [[Japan]].  Its name includes one [[kanji]] from {{Nihongo|[[Hida Province|Hida]]|\u98db\u9a28\u56fd}} and one from {{Nihongo|[[Etch\u016b Province|Etch\u016b]]|\u8d8a\u4e2d\u56fd}}, the names of the provinces that were in use at the time. The earthquake is estimated to have killed 200\u2013300 people.  It also caused the Mount Tonbi Landslide and blocked the upper reaches of the [[J\u014dganji River]].<ref name=\"Hietsu\">{{cite web|url=http://cais.gsi.go.jp/KAIHOU/kaihou33/03_05.pdf|title=The Hietsu Earthquake of April 9, 1858 and the Omachi Earthquake of April 23, 1858|last=Usami|first=Tatsuo|language=Japanese|publisher=Earthquake Research Institute, University of Tokyo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304141331/http://cais.gsi.go.jp/KAIHOU/kaihou33/03_05.pdf|archivedate=March 4, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1872|03|18}} || 7.1 ''M<sub>K</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000551}}551 (official confirmed) || 1872 Hamada earthquake || \u6d5c\u7530\u5730\u9707 || ''Hamada Jishin'' || off coast [[Hamada, Shimane|Hamada, Shimane Prefecture]] || According to the official confirmed report, 4506 houses were damaged by the earthquake, 230 houses were burned, 551 people were killed, and landslides destroyed 6567 homes in the affected area. This quake occurred at 16:40 local time.\n|-\n| {{dts|1880|02|22}} || 5.5\u20136.0 || 0 || 1880 Yokohama earthquake || \u6a2a\u6d5c\u5730\u9707 || ''Yokohama Jishin'' || Yokohama City || The damage was minor. However, the [[Seismological Society of Japan]] was established in response to the quake.<ref>[https://typhoon.yahoo.co.jp/weather/calendar/173/ \u6a2a\u6d5c\u5730\u9707\uff081880\u5e74\uff09] Japan,Yahoo\uff08Japa