ke Research Promotion}}</ref> The death toll was 31 killed and 157 injured.\n|-\n| {{dts|1894|10|22}} || 7.0 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000726}}726 (Official confirmed) || 1894 Sh\u014dkai earthquake || \u5e84\u5185\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dnai Jishin'' || [[Sakata, Yamagata|Sakata]], [[Yamagata Prefecture]] || According to the official confirmed report, 14,118 houses and buildings were damaged and 2,148 were burned. There were 726 human fatalities and 8,403 people injured in the damaged area. A large-scale fire broke out in Sakata, and around the Shonai plain area, many instances of cracked earth, sinking ground, sand boils, and fountains were observed.\n|-\n| {{dts|1896|06|15}} || 8.5 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|022000}}22,000+<ref>{{cite web| url= https://earthquake.usgs.gov/learn/today/index.php?month=6&day=15&submit=View+Date| title=Today in Earthquake History|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1896 Sanriku earthquake]] || \u660e\u6cbb\u4e09\u9678\u5730\u9707 || ''Meiji Sanriku Jishin'' || &nbsp; || This quake occurred off the coast of [[Sanriku, Iwate|Sanriku]] in [[Iwate Prefecture]], which caused a [[tsunami]] of {{convert|25|m|ft|abbr=on}} to strike 35 minutes after the quake, destroying hundreds of houses and killed over 22,000 people. Tsunami were also observed as far away as Hawaii and in California.<ref name=\"meijisanriku-agu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agu.org/news/press/pr_archives/1996-1999/sanriku.html|title=Research describes origin of devastating tsunami|publisher=American Geophysical Union|date=1996-06-12|accessdate=2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name=\"meijisanriku-usgs\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1896_06_15.php|title=Historic Earthquakes: Sanriku, Japan, 1896 June 15 UTC , Magnitude 8.5|publisher=[[US Geological Survey]]|date=2009-01-29|accessdate=2009-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509154555/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1896_06_15.php|archive-date=2009-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1923|09|01}} || 8.3 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|142800}} 142,800<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/learn/today/index.php?month=9&day=1&submit=View+Date|title=Today in Earthquake History|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>||[[1923 Great Kant\u014d earthquake]] || \u5927\u6b63\u95a2\u6771\u5730\u9707<br>(\u95a2\u6771\u5927\u9707\u707d) || ''Taish\u014d Kant\u014d Jishin''<br>(''Kant\u014d Daishinsai'') || [[Izu \u014cshima]] || An earthquake which struck the [[Kant\u014d]] plain on the [[Japan]]ese main island of [[Honsh\u016b]] at 11:58 on the morning of September 1, 1923.  Varied accounts hold that the duration of the earthquake was between 4 and 10 minutes. The quake had an epicenter deep beneath [[Izu \u014cshima]] Island in [[Sagami Bay]]. It devastated [[Tokyo]], the port city of [[Yokohama]], and the surrounding prefectures of [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], and [[Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka]], and caused widespread damage throughout the Kant\u014d region.<ref>Hammer, Joshua. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=6O8VyhDbUPgC  ''Yokohama Burning: the Deadly 1923 Earthquake and Fire that Helped Forge the Path to World War II,'' p. 278], citing Francis Hawks,  (1856). ''Narrative of the Expedition of an American Squadron to the China Seas and Japan Performed in the Years 1852, 1853 and 1854 under the Command of Commodore M.C. Perry, United States Navy,'' Washington: A.O.P. Nicholson by order of Congress, 1856; originally published in ''Senate Executive Documents'', No. 34 of 33rd Congress, 2nd Session.</ref>  The power and intensity of the earthquake is easy to underestimate, but the 1923 earthquake managed to move the 93-ton [[K\u014dtoku-in|Great Buddha]] statue at [[Kamakura, Kanagawa|Kamakura]].  The statue slid forward almost two feet.<ref>Great Buddha: [http://pacific-islander.blogspot.com/2007/10/all-buddhas-great-and-small.html blog]</ref> Casualty estimates range up to about 142,800 deaths, a figure including approximately 40,000 who went missing and were presumed dead.\n|-\n| {{dts|1925|05|23}} || 6.8 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000428}}428 ||1925 Kita Tajima earthquake || \u5317\u4f46\u99ac\u5730\u9707 || ''Kita Tajima Jishin'' || [[Toyooka]] in [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]] ||This earthquake's epicenter was (35.6 degrees north latitude, 134.8 degrees east longitude), in the Maruyama River estuary. According to the Japanese government's official report, there were 428 human fatalities, 1,016 people injured, 7,863 buildings destroyed, and 45,659 houses damaged by collapse or fire. This quake caused extensive damage to the town of Toyooka and the Maruyama River area. Just before the shaking could be felt, a sound like a cannon was reportedly heard intermittently from the direction of the estuary near the Maruyama River. During the earthquake, the ground in the town of Tokyooka experienced strong seismic vibrations for 16 seconds. As most of the buildings of the time were wooden, many of them were destroyed at once during the initial earthquake. In the fire that broke out subsequently, half of Toyooka was burned down, with many deaths resulting (a reported 8% of the town's population.) 272 deaths were confirmed to have occurred in the Kinosaki area.\n|-\n| {{dts|1927|03|07}} || 7.6 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|003020}}3,020 ||[[1927 Kita Tango earthquake]] || \u5317\u4e39\u5f8c\u5730\u9707 || ''Kita Tango Jishin'' || [[Tango Peninsula]] in [[Kyoto Prefecture]] || Almost all of the houses in Mineyama (now part of [[Ky\u014dtango, Kyoto|Ky\u014dtango]]) were destroyed, and the quake was felt as far away as [[Tokyo]] and [[Kagoshima]].<ref name=\"kitatango-usgs\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1927_03_07.php|title=Historic Earthquakes: Tango, Japan, 1927 March 07 09:27 UTC, Magnitude 7.6|publisher=[[USGS]]|accessdate=2009-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509130409/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1927_03_07.php|archive-date=2009-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1930|11|26}} || 7.3 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000272}}272 ||[[1930 North Izu earthquake]] || 1930\u5e74\u5317\u4f0a\u8c46\u5730\u9707 || ''Sen-ky\u016bhyaku-sanj\u016b-nen Kita-Izu Jishin'' || [[Izu Peninsula]] || \n|-\n| {{dts|1933|03|02}} || 8.4 ''M<sub>w</sub>''<ref>Kanamori, H. ( 1977), [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/4982/ce0d7cef9194cc5d95fc823bb888c3eae505.pdf The energy release in great earthquakes], J. Geophys. Res., 82( 20), 2981\u2013 2987, {{doi|10.1029/JB082i020p02981}}.</ref> ||{{Hs|003000}}3,000+ ||[[1933 Sanriku earthquake]] || \u662d\u548c\u4e09\u9678\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dwa Sanriku Jishin'' || {{convert|290|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the city of [[Kamaishi, Iwate]] ||[[File:Kamaishi Bay after 1933 tsunami.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Kamaishi Bay, Iwate after 1933 earthquake and tsunami]] A major [[earthquake]] whose associated [[tsunami]] caused widespread damage to towns on the [[Iwate Prefecture|Sanriku]] coast of the [[T\u014dhoku region]] of [[Honsh\u016b]], [[Japan]] in 1933.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1933_03_02.php |title=Historical Earthquakes:The 1933 Sanriku earthquake |accessdate=2008-07-16 |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=14 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724115436/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1933_03_02.php |archive-date=2008-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1936|11|03}} || 7.2 ''M<sub>s</sub>'' ||0||[[1936 Miyagi earthquake]] || 1936\u5e74\u5bae\u57ce\u770c\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Sen-ky\u016bhyaku-sanj\u016broku-nen Miyagi-ken-oki Jishin'' || offshore [[Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi]] \n|\n|-\n| {{dts|1943|09|10}} || 7.2 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|001083}}1,083 ||[[1943 Tottori earthquake]] || \u9ce5\u53d6\u5730\u9707 || ''Tottori Jishin'' || offshore from [[Ketaka District, Tottori|Ketaka District]] || An earthquake which occurred in [[Tottori prefecture]], [[Japan]] at 17:36 on September 10, 1943. Although the earthquake occurred during [[World War II]], information about the disaster was surprisingly [[Censorship in the Empire of Japan|uncensored]], and relief volunteers and supplies came from many parts of the Japanese empire, including [[Manchukuo]]. The Tottori earthquake had its [[epicenter]] offshore from [[Ketaka District, Tottori|Ketaka District]], now part of [[Tottori, Tottori|Tottori city]], with a magnitude of 7.2 on the [[Richter magnitude scale|Richter Scale]]. The magnitude of the earthquake was 6.0 in Tottori city, and 5.0 as far away as [[Okayama, Okayama|Okayama]] on the [[Seto Inland Sea|Inland Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hp1039.jishin.go.jp/eqchreng/8-2-2.htm|title=The Tottori Earthquake (September 10, 1943, M 7.2)|publisher=The Headquarters for Earthquake Research Promotion}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1944|12|07}} || 8.1 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|001223}}1,223 ||[[1944 T\u014dnankai earthquake]] || \u662d\u548c\u6771\u5357\u6d77\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dwa T\u014dnankai Jishin'' || {{coord|34.0|137.1}} || This earthquake occurred on Dec. 7, 1944, at 13:35 local time (04:35 UTC). Its [[moment magnitude scale|moment magnitude]] was 8.1 and it was felt with a maximum intensity of 5 on the [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|Shindo scale]] (or VII, \"Severe\", on the [[Mercalli intensity scale]]). It struck the provinces along the coast of the [[T\u014dkai region]], causing serious damage and triggering a tsunami. The [[earthquake]] and [[tsunami]] combined killed 1,223 people, with injuries reported to have affected 20,000 people or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=3791&t=101650&s=13&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Significant Earthquake|author=Paula Dunbar|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1945|01|13}} || 6.8 ''M<sub>L</sub>'' ||{{Hs|001180}}1180 + 1126 missing ||[[1945 Mikawa earthquake]] || \u4e09\u6cb3\u5730\u9707 || ''Mikawa Jishin'' || [[Mikawa Bay]] || An earthquake which occurred off [[Mie prefecture|Mie]] and [[Aichi prefecture]]s, [[Japan]] at 03:38 on January 13, 1945. As the earthquake occurred during [[World War II]], information about the disaster was [[Censorship in the Empire of Japan|censored]], and efforts at keeping the disaster secret hampered relief efforts and contributed to a high death toll.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://bases.bireme.br/cgi-bin/wxislind.exe/iah/online/?IsisScript=iah/iah.xis&src=google&base=DESASTRES&lang=p&nextAction=lnk&exprSearch=1920&indexSearch=ID|title=Interpretation of damage to houses and casualties relied on a precise evaluation of earthquake ground motions in the epicentral region: 1945 Mikawa earthquake|journal=En|pages=378\u2013393|last1=Inada|first1=Osamu|last2=Mochizuki|first2=Toshio|last3=Miura|first3=Fusanori|last4=Taniguchi|first4=Hitoshi}}</ref> The Mikawa earthquake had its [[epicenter]] offshore in [[Mikawa Bay]] ({{coord|34|42.1|N|137|6.8|E|type:event}} at a depth of eleven kilometers). The city of [[Tsu, Mie|Tsu]] recorded a magnitude of 6 on the [[Richter magnitude scale|Richter Scale]]; however, areas in southern Aichi prefecture were closer to the epicenter, and suffered significant damage.\n|-\n| {{dts|1946|12|20}} || 8.1 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|001362}}1,362 ||[[1946 Nankai earthquake]] || \u662d\u548c\u5357\u6d77\u5730\u9707 || ''Sh\u014dwa Nankai Jishin'' || [[Nankai Trough]] || A major [[earthquake]] in [[Nankaid\u014d]], [[Japan]].  Occurred on December 20, 1946 at 19:19 UTC. The earthquake was felt from Northern [[Honsh\u016b]] to [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref name=Nakaido>{{cite web |url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1946_12_20.php |title=The 1946 Nankaido earthquake |accessdate=2008-06-29 |publisher=[[USGS]] |date=13 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601172947/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/regional/world/events/1946_12_20.php |archive-date=2008-06-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|