Island]] were forced to evacuate as houses collapsed and landslides occurred in places. Investigations subsequent to the earthquake determined that the new fault was most likely an extension of the known Kego Fault that runs through the center of the city.\n|-\n| {{dts|2005|08|16}} || 7.2 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000000}}0 ||[[2005 Miyagi earthquake]] || \u5bae\u57ce\u770c\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Miyagi-ken Oki Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Miyagi Prefecture</span>about {{convert|55|km|mi|abbr=on}} due east of the [[Oshika Peninsula]] in [[Miyagi Prefecture]] || A powerful [[earthquake]] that struck the east coast of the [[Japan]]ese island of [[Honsh\u016b]] at 11:46 (02:46 [[UTC]]) on August 16, causing casualties, building collapses and [[power outage]]s.  The earthquake began on Tuesday, August 16, 2005, and affected Japan's northeastern coast. It triggered a tsunami warning, and buildings shook 200 miles away in the capital, Tokyo. It was initially estimated to have a rating of 6.8., and the U.S. Geological Survey later registered it as a 7.2.<ref>{{cite web|date=August 16, 2005 |title=Quake Shakes Buildings in Tokyo |work=The Associated Press |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/07/light-quake-shakes-buildings-in-tokyo-no-injuries-or-damage.html |accessdate=2006-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207185046/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/07/light-quake-shakes-buildings-in-tokyo-no-injuries-or-damage.html |archivedate=February 7, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|11|15}} || 8.3 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000000}}0 ||[[2006 Kuril Islands earthquake]] || 2006\u5e74\u5343\u5cf6\u5217\u5cf6\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Nisen-roku-nen Chishima Rett\u014d Oki Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Kuril Islands</span> about {{convert|160|km|mi|abbr=on}} due east of the southern tip of [[Simushir]] in the [[Kuril Islands]] || The earthquake happened at 20:29 [[Japan Standard Time|JST]] on November 15, 2006, causing a [[tsunami]] to hit the Japanese northern coast.\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|01|13}} || 8.1 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000000}}0 ||[[2007 Kuril Islands earthquake]] || 2007\u5e74\u5343\u5cf6\u5217\u5cf6\u6c96\u5730\u9707 || ''Nisen-nana-nen Chishima Rett\u014d Oki Jishin'' ||  {{coord|46|28.8|N|154|04.48|E|type:event}} || The earthquake happened at 1:23&nbsp;p.m. [[Japan Standard Time|JST]]  (04:23 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) and resulted in a [[tsunami]] warning but did not cause significant damage.<ref name=GIANT-EARTHQUAKE-HITS-JAPAN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ens-newswire.com/ens/jan2007/2007-01-12-06.asp|title=Giant Earthquake Jolts Japan, But Tsunami Warnings Cancelled|last=staff|website=www.ens-newswire.com}}</ref> The epicentre was located 95&nbsp;km to the south east of the [[2006 Kuril Islands earthquake]] that struck a few weeks earlier.\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|03|25}} || 6.9 ''M<sub>w</sub>'' ||{{Hs|000001}}1 ||[[2007 Noto earthquake]] || \u80fd\u767b\u534a\u5cf6\u5730\u9707 || ''Noto Hant\u014d Jishin'' || <span style=\"display:none\">Ishikawa Prefecture</span>about {{convert|11|km|mi|abbr=on}} due west of the southern end of the town of [[Wajima, Ishikawa|Wajima]] || At 9:42&nbsp;a.m., a [[Richter magnitude scale|magnitude]] 6.9 [[earthquake]], struck the [[Hokuriku region]] of Japan, near the [[Noto Peninsula]]. The earthquake shook the city of [[Nanao, Ishikawa|Nanao]] and the town of [[Anamizu, Ishikawa|Anamizu]] with a [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|seismic intensity]] of 6+ on Japan's [[Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale|''shindo'' scale]]. One death, in the city of [[Wajima, Ishikawa|Wajima]], and at least 214 injuries have been reported.  A [[tsunami]] advisory was immediately made for the [[Kaga, Ishikawa|Kaga]] coast and Noto coast, and a 10\u201320&nbsp;cm wave hit shore about 30 minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070326a1.html|title=Hokuriku quake kills one, injures 170|publishe