{"title_page": "Indian blogosphere", "text_new": "'''Indian blogosphere''' (or '''IndiBlogosphere''') is the online predominantly community of [[India]]n [[weblog]]s that is part of the larger [[blogosphere]].<ref>Hindi Blogging Ka Itihas, Author- [[Ravindra Prabhat]], Publisher-Hindi Sahitya Niketan, Bijnor, India, Year- 2011, p. 180, {{ISBN|978-93-80916-14-9}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWith the advent of [[unicode]] when typing in [[Languages of India|Indian languages]] on computer became possible, blogs in Indian languages started to be written. Initially due to a lack of [[Indic scripts|Indic]] typing tools, the early Indian blogosphere was small. Greater awareness and availability of Indic typing tools led to rapid growth in blogs written in Indian languages.<ref>Hindi Bloging : Abhivyakti ki Nayi Kranti, Editor- Awinash Bachaspati/[[Ravindra Prabhat]], Publisher-Hindi Sahitya Niketan, Bijnor, India, Year- 2011,Pages: 376,{{ISBN|978-93-80916-05-7}}</ref>\n\n==Indic language typing tools==\nAlthough the standard keyboard of Indian languages is [[Inscript|InScript]] yet Phonetic transliteration based typing became most popular for Unicode Indic typing in spite of its drawbacks.  The two most popular phonetic typing tools of old times are \"Indic IME\" and \"BarahaIME\". In 2007, with the advent of the [[Google Indic Transliteration]] tool in its blogging service [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]], it became the tool of choice for new bloggers because it is dictionary based and does not need a learning curve.\n\n==Blog platform==\nIndia has over 20 [[Languages with official status in India|official languages]] and yet most Indian blogs are still written in English. However, recently, blogging in [[Bangla (language)|Bangla]] has been on the rise. These blogs are written as stand-alone blogs or on popular blogging platforms.\nAmong Indian blogs written in languages other than English, Google's [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]] is the most popular among Indian bloggers because it supports [[Indic Unicode]] and has rich features. In 2007, the Indic language typing tool [[Google Indic Transliteration]] was also integrated into it, so no separate Indic typing tool was needed. Blogspot (Blogger) also provide the facility of custom domain redirects such as .com, in and others. Earlier there was only http:// for custom domain but now there is https:// facility for custom domain also which enhance security features.\n\nIn addition to this, [[WordPress]] being supporting [[Indic Unicode]], is most popular among those who host their blog on their own domain.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Blogosphere]]\n*[[Draft:TamilRadar|Tamilradar]]\n*[[Hindi Blogosphere]]\n*[[Online journalism in India]]\n*[[Tamil Blogosphere]]\n*[[Webcomics in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Indic computing]]\n[[Category:Indian bloggers| ]]\n[[Category:Blogospheres]]\n", "text_old": "'''Indian blogosphere''' (or '''IndiBlogosphere''') is the online predominantly community of [[India]]n [[weblog]]s that is part of the larger [[blogosphere]].<ref>Hindi Blogging Ka Itihas, Author- [[Ravindra Prabhat]], Publisher-Hindi Sahitya Niketan, Bijnor, India, Year- 2011, p. 180, {{ISBN|978-93-80916-14-9}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWith the advent of [[unicode]] when typing in [[Languages of India|Indian languages]] on computer became possible, blogs in Indian languages started to be written. Initially due to a lack of [[Indic scripts|Indic]] typing tools, the early Indian blogosphere was small. Greater awareness and availability of Indic typing tools led to rapid growth in blogs written in Indian languages.<ref>Hindi Bloging : Abhivyakti ki Nayi Kranti, Editor- Awinash Bachaspati/[[Ravindra Prabhat]], Publisher-Hindi Sahitya Niketan, Bijnor, India, Year- 2011,Pages: 376,{{ISBN|978-93-80916-05-7}}</ref>\n\n==Indic language typing tools==\nAlthough the standard keyboard of Indian languages is [[Inscript|InScript]] yet Phonetic transliteration based typing became most popular for Unicode Indic typing in spite of its drawbacks.  The two most popular phonetic typing tools of old times are \"Indic IME\" and \"BarahaIME\". In 2007, with the advent of the [[Google Indic Transliteration]] tool in its blogging service [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]], it became the tool of choice for new bloggers because it is dictionary based and does not need a learning curve.\n\n==Blog platform==\nIndia has over 20 [[Languages with official status in India|official languages]] and yet most Indian blogs are still written in English. However, recently, blogging in [[Bangla (language)|Bangla]] has been on the rise. These blogs are written as stand-alone blogs or on popular blogging platforms.\nAmong Indian blogs written in languages other than English, Google's [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]] is the most popular among Indian bloggers because it supports [[Indic Unicode]] and has rich features. In 2007, the Indic language typing tool [[Google Indic Transliteration]] was also integrated into it, so no separate Indic typing tool was needed. Blogspot (Blogger) also provide the facility of custom domain redirects such as .com, in and others. Earlier there was only http:// for custom domain but now there is https:// facility for custom domain also which enhance security features.\n\nIn addition to this, [[WordPress]] being supporting [[Indic Unicode]], is most popular among those who host their blog on their own domain.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Blogosphere]]\n*[[Hindi Blogosphere]]\n*[[Online journalism in India]]\n*[[Tamil Blogosphere]]\n*[[Webcomics in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Indic computing]]\n[[Category:Indian bloggers| ]]\n[[Category:Blogospheres]]\n", "name_user": "Radarofficial", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_blogosphere"}
{"title_page": "FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual cross-country skiing event}}\n{{Infobox ski tour\n| name               = FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals\n| image              = \n| image_caption      = \n| image_alt          =\n| imagesize          = \n| series             = \n| date               = Mid-March \n| venue              = Various\n| english            =\n| localnames         =\n| nickname           =  \n| competition        = [[FIS Cross-Country World Cup]]\n| type               = Mini-tour\n| organiser          = [[International Ski Federation]]\n| director           =\n| first              = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2008|3|14}}\n| number             = 11 (as of [[2018\u201319 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2019]])\n| last               =  \n| firstwinner_men    = {{flagathlete|[[Vincent Vittoz]]|FRA}}\n| mostwins_men       = {{flagathlete|[[Petter Northug]]|NOR}} \n:(''3 wins'')\n| mostrecent_men     = {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Johannes H\u00f8sflot Kl\u00e6bo]]|NOR}} }}\n| firstwinner_ladies = {{flagathlete|[[Virpi Kuitunen]]|FIN}}\n| mostwins_ladies    = {{flagathlete|[[Marit Bj\u00f8rgen]]|NOR}}\n:(''6 wins'')\n| mostrecent_ladies  = {{flagathlete|[[Stina Nilsson]]|SWE}}\n}}\nThe '''FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals''' is a [[cross-country skiing (sport)|cross-country skiing]] event held annually since the [[2007\u201308 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2007\u201308 season]] in various places in [[Europe]] or [[Canada]]. The World Cup Finals is a Stage World Cup event in the [[FIS Cross-Country World Cup]], and are held as the last World Cup race weekend of the season. The inaugural World Cup Finals was held in 2008 in [[Bormio]], Italy. As of the [[2018\u201319 FIS Cross-Country World Cup|2018\u201319 season]], the World Cup Finals consists of three stages; a sprint, a mass start race and a [[Pursuit racing#Winter sports|pursuit]].\n\nThe first stages was arranged on 14 March 2008 and were won by [[Claudia K\u00fcnzel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medias3.fis-ski.com/pdf/2008/CC/2894/2008CC2894RL.pdf |title=Prologue Ladies 2.5 km Free Individual Results |date=14 March 2008|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> (ladies) and [[Pietro Piller Cottrer]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medias1.fis-ski.com/pdf/2008/CC/2893/2008CC2893RL.pdf |title=Prologue Men 3.3 km Free Individual Results |date=14 March 2008|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> (men). The first overall winners of the World Cup Finals were [[Virpi Kuitunen]] and [[Vincent Vittoz]].\n\n==Venues==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=center;\n! Year\n! Venue\n|-\n| [[2007\u201308 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2008]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Bormio]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Stockholm]] and [[Falun]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Stockholm and Falun\n|-\n| 2011\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Stockholm and Falun\n|-\n| 2012\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Stockholm and Falun\n|-\n| 2013\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Stockholm and Falun\n|-\n| 2014\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Falun\n|-\n| 2015\n| align=left|''not arranged''\n|-\n| [[2016 Ski Tour Canada|2016]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Gatineau]], [[Montreal]], [[Quebec City]], [[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]] and [[Lake Louise, Alberta|Lake Louise]]\n|-\n| [[2016\u201317 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2017]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} Quebec City\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2018]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} Falun\n|-\n| [[2018\u201319 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2019]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} Quebec City\n|-\n| 2020\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} <s>[[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]]</s> Cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n|-\n| ''2021''\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Beijing]]\n|}\n\n==Prize money==\nAs of the 2018\u201319 edition, a total of [[Swiss franc|CHF]] 240,000, both genders included, is awarded in cash prizes in the race.{{sfn|''Rules for the FIS Cross-Country World Cup''|2018|pp=41}} The overall winners of the World Cup Finals receive CHF 22,500, with the second and third placed skiers getting CHF 17,500 and CHF 11,000 respectively.{{sfn|''Rules for the FIS Cross-Country World Cup''|2018|pp=41}} All finishers in the top 20 are awarded money.{{sfn|''Rules for the FIS Cross-Country World Cup''|2018|pp=41}}  CHF 5,000 is given to the winners of each stage of the race, with smaller amounts given to places 2 and 3.{{sfn|''Rules for the FIS Cross-Country World Cup''|2018|pp=41}}\n\n==Overall winners==\n{| border=\"0\"\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n===Men===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"min-width:40%\"\n! Year\n! Winner\n! Second\n! Third\n|-\n| 2008\n| align=left|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Vincent Vittoz]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Luk\u00e1\u0161 Bauer]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Giorgio Di Centa]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Vincent Vittoz]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Alexander Legkov]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Maurice Manificat]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Marcus Hellner]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Finn H\u00e5gen Krogh]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Dario Cologna]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Devon Kershaw]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Niklas Dyrhaug]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Petter Northug]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Finn H\u00e5gen Krogh]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Martin Johnsrud Sundby]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Martin Johnsrud Sundby]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Alex Harvey (skier)|Alex Harvey]]\n| align=left|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Alexander Legkov]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| colspan=3|''not arranged''\n|-\n| 2016\n| align=left|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Martin Jo