-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Johannes H\u00f8sflot Kl\u00e6bo]]|NOR}} || [[2016\u201317 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2017]], [[2018\u201319 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2019]]\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=2 | 1 || {{flagathlete|[[Vincent Vittoz]]|FRA}} || [[2007\u201308 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2008]]\n|-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alexander Bolshunov]]|RUS}} || [[2017\u201318 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2018]]\n|}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Ladies\n! Wins || Skier || Editions\n|-\n| align=center | 6 || {{flagathlete|[[Marit Bj\u00f8rgen]]|NOR}} || 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, [[2016\u201317 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2017]], [[2017\u201318 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2018]]\n|-\n| align=center | 2 || {{flagathlete|[[Therese Johaug]]|NOR}} || 2014, [[2016 Ski Tour Canada|2016]]\n|-\n| align=center rowspan=3 | 1 ||{{flagathlete|[[Virpi Kuitunen]]|FIN}} || [[2007\u201308 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2008]]\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Justyna Kowalczyk]]|POL}} || 2009\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Stina Nilsson]]|SWE}} || [[2018\u201319 FIS Cross-Country World Cup Finals|2019]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==World Cup points==\nThe overall winner are awarded 200 points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://res.cloudinary.com/fis-production/image/upload/v1540454291/fis-prod/Rules_WC_CC_1819_oct2018_all.pdf |title=Rules for the FIS Cross-country World Cup |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] (FIS) |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> The winners of each of the three stages are awarded 50 points. The maximum number of points an athlete can earn is therefore 350 points.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; \n|- bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\"\n! Position\n| width=20|1 || width=20| 2 || width=20| 3 || width=20| 4 || width=20| 5 || width=20| 6 || width=20| 7 || width=20| 8 || width=20| 9 || width=20| 10 || width=20| 11 || width=20| 12 || width=20| 13 || width=20| 14 || width=20| 15 || width=20| 16 || width=20| 17 || width=20| 18 || width=20